Whether a woman is legally married or not, she always has the support of her family throughout her pregnancy and delivery. “We firmly believe this,” explains Sangay Pema, a women’s rights activist. “In poorer families, expectant mothers may even receive a portion of their in-laws’ land.”

A highly respected woman in Bhutan’s political and social life is Her Majesty the Queen. Her Majesty has chaired the National Commission for Women and Children and, more recently, the National Commission for the Rights of the Child, both offices vital to the region’s greater advancement. In addition, Rapaxon Tshering has served as the secretary general of the Association of Bhutanese Women’s Development in India and Nepal, focusing her work on gender, ethnicity, and interfaith issues.

The publication of two books was the most significant highlight in 2015 for Dr. Asha Singh, PhD, a member of Jamyang Buddhist College in Shechen Monastery. Dr. Asha did her highest studies at Oxford and is one of the few noted Indian academics in the region with a speciality in the social history of Bhutan. Obliging an “urgent need to rethink Bhutan’s past,” says Dr. Asha, recently published books of social and cultural history have refuted Bhutan’s old established view of its inner workings.
